Goal

Choosing a subset of 4 or 5 quantitative variables and explore linear relationships.

library(moments)
library(corrplot)
## corrplot 0.84 loaded
cars = read.delim("/home/mehdi/Bureau/ida_hmw_1.2/cars.txt", sep = "", dec = ".")

For this part, we decided to choose 5 qualitative variables : mpg, displacement, horsepower, weight and acceleration We created a new data set with only these 5 qualitative variables : carsquali

carsquali=as.data.frame(cars[,3:6], title=TRUE)
carsquali$mpg <- cars$mpg

We just displayed below the R-matrix. We can visualize it with a plot showing the correlation between the variables in a more intuitive way :

corrplot(r, method = "circle")

Which variables are correlated the most ?

diag(r)=0
which(r==max(abs(r)), arr.ind=TRUE)
##              row col
## weight         3   1
## displacement   1   3

The more correlated variables are weight and displacement which is logical because physically, displacement is strongly related to the car’s weight. Indeed, the correlation between these two variable is : 0.9128930 which is very high. We have a very strong linear relationship which implies that variables are measuring almost the same thing. However, in absolute value, the correlation between all these variables apart between acceleration and weight (0.4985387) and between acceleration and mpg (0.4747480) are high. We have a strong relationship implying that we can be confident that these two variables are connected in some way.

Visualizing partial correlations

library(corrgram)
library(corrplot)
corrgram(matrix.partial,
         lower.panel=panel.shade, upper.panel=panel.pie,
         diag.panel=panel.minmax, text.panel=panel.txt)

corrplot.mixed(matrix.partial,order="AOE" )

Displaying the plots, we can see that partial correlations are closer to zero than ordinary correlations. In this case, this is suggesting that the relationship between the variables of interest could be explained by their common relationships to the explanatory variables upon which we are conditioning.

Coefficient of determination

Define a function r2multv for squared multiple correlation coeficients

r2multv<-function(x){
  r2s=1-1/(diag(solve(cov(x)))*diag(cov(x)))
  r2s
}

use it on data set “carsquali”

r2multv(carsquali)
## displacement   horsepower       weight acceleration          mpg 
##    0.9159490    0.8662318    0.8984768    0.6745925    0.8320842
